  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards\n- Develops recommendations for preventing money laundering\n- Most countries follow its guidelines\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n- Provide frameworks for international cooperation\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Establishes guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) standards\n- Provides guidelines and monitors countries' anti-money laundering efforts\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Sets specific regulations for EU member states\n\n6. Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- While primarily a U.S. law, it has significant international impact\n\nMost countries have implemented national laws requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
